 the Atlantic. They discuss in their essays the state of historiography and reflect on problems of theory and methodology. Through compelling case studies, focusing on the nation and nationalism, military and war, colonialism, politics and protest, class and citizenship, religion, Jewish and non-Jewish Germans, the Holocaust, the body and sexuality and the family, this volume demonstrates the extraordinary power of the gender perspective to challenge existing interpretations and rewrite mainstream arguments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aFeminist theory. 0aHistoriographyzGermany. 0aHistoriographyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aCanning, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Belinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossmann, Atina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoonz, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKundrus, Birthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaria Baader, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoeller, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuataert, Jean H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuataert, Jean H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchaser, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor Allen, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Co